The mature parasitoid emerges a week later by cutting a hole in the aphid skin.

column2: An aphid predator used as a biocontrol agent for all species of aphid
column6: The adults are small, less than 1/8 inch long, black, delicate flies with a lifespan of about 10 days. They feed on aphid honeydew. Larvae are small, bright orange maggots. The female flies deposit orange eggs within the aphid colony. Larvae inject a toxin into aphids leg joints to paralyse them and then suck out the aphid body contents through a hole bitten in the thorax. The larvae drop to the ground and burrow into the soil to pupate.

column6: Adult is 4-6mm long and body is covered with fine, light hairs. The female lays her eggs close to the thistle flowerhead. Larvae consume the flower and developing seeds thus stopping germination of the next plant generation. Larvae go on to pupate on the flowerhead remains. Host specific. One generation per year and adults live approximately 2 months. Dislikes cool climates.

Typically only one generation of weevil occur each year.

column2: An aphid parasitoid used as a biocontrol agent for aphids
column6: Tiny, slender, black insect with brown legs, long antennae and conspicuous wing venation. The female has a pointed abdomen, while the male's abdomen is round-shaped. The female wasp injects an egg in the aphid with her ovipositor. Hatched larvae eat the aphid from the inside leading to the formation of a a golden-brown, leathery mummy. Finally, a new adult parasitic wasp leaves the mummy through a round hole.

column2: An aphid parasitoid used as a biocontrol agent for aphids particularly Myzus Spp.
column6: A relatively small black braconid wasp, about an eighth of an inch long. Females lay eggs singly in aphid nymphs. On hatching, the wasp larvae consume the aphids from inside eventually killing them. The larva pupates inside the aphid cadaver which has developed a characteristic round, golden brown, mummified appearance. The mature parasitoid emerges a week later by cutting a hole in the aphid skin.

column2: An aphid predator used as a biocontrol agent for all species of aphid
column6: The adults are small, less than 1/8 inch long, black, delicate flies with a lifespan of about 10 days. They feed on aphid honeydew. Larvae are small, bright orange maggots. The female flies deposit orange eggs within the aphid colony. Larvae inject a toxin into aphids leg joints to paralyse them and then suck out the aphid body contents through a hole bitten in the thorax. The larvae drop to the ground and burrow into the soil to pupate.

column2: A small phytophagous weevil that can be used for the biological control of thistle particularly the yellow star thistle
column6: Adult is 4-6mm long and body is covered with fine, light hairs. The female lays her eggs close to the thistle flowerhead. Larvae consume the flower and developing seeds thus stopping germination of the next plant generation. Larvae go on to pupate on the flowerhead remains. Host specific. One generation per year and adults live approximately 2 months. Dislikes cool climates.

column2: A parasitic wasp that can be used for the biocontrol of the alfalfa weevil that is a serious economic pest of lucerne in many parts of the world including North America
column6: Small black wasps about 3mm in length with stout bodies. Adult wasps lay their eggs within the weevil larvae, as the eggs hatch they feed internally on the larvae killing it.  Only one parasitoid can develop inside the host weevil eventually emerging to spin a cocoon. These cocoons are 3-4mm long, oval shaped, brown in colour wit ha cream central band. Typically only one generation of weevil occur each year.

column2: A predator of whiteflies and armoured scale which can be used for their biological control
column6: The wasp is tiny (~0.6mm long). Males are completely black whereas females are black with a yellow abdomen and opalescent wings. Females deposit their eggs inside nymphs or pupae of the host whitefly. The wasp larvae develop and feed on their host. Wasp pupation occurs within the whitefly body, from which adult wasps emerge about 10 days after.

column2: A predator of blackflies that can be used for their biological control
column6: The wasp is tiny (~1mm long). The males are completely dark brown whereas females have different markings. The thorax is straw coloured, the wings are transparent with a smoky patch in the centre and the legs are whitish-grey. Females deposit their eggs inside nymphs or pupae of the host whitefly. The wasp larvae develop and feed on their host. Wasp pupation occurs within the whitefly body, from which adult wasps emerge about 10 days after.

column6: Adults are small brownish weevils, 4-5mm long, covered with stiff grayish hairs.  Larvae are C-shaped grubs. Female weevils chew into the side of a young puncture vine bur, deposit eggs into the seed and seal it with faecal material. Weevils grubs develop inside the seed and pupate therein. This activity significantly reduces seed production.
